replies:
['Well my friend, an octave has 8 notes. If we start at A: A B C D E F G A (at a higher pitch). But then if we look at the 12-step Western Music scale, an octave can be said to have 12 notes, because you include the semitones: A# C# D# F# G# and we curiously donâ€™t include the higher pitched A in our count (probably because humans like even numbers).
This is how the frets of a guitar are laid out. But if you include the microtonal â€œin betweenâ€ notes, well you can make however many notes/frets in an octave as you want.
So you see, music is relative, and Joey realizes that the only thing that really matters is the ability to melt your face with his guitar playing while wearing blue crocs.
Have a good day!']

Microtonality is the use in music of microtones â€” intervals smaller than a semitone, also called "microintervals". It may also be extended to include any music using intervals not found in the customary Western tuning of twelve equal intervals per octave. In other words, a microtone may be thought of as a note that falls "between the keys" of a piano tuned in equal temperament.
